    "name": "George Butler",
    "profile": "American record producer, label executive and A&R man. Born on 2 September 1931 in  Charlotte, N.C., U.S. - Died on 9 April 2008 in Castro Valley, California, U.S.\r\nHe worked for a number of well-known jazz record labels from the 1960s to the 1990s including [l=United Artists Records], [l=Blue Note] Records (1972-1976, producer), and [l=Columbia] Records (A&R executive, after 1978). When Columbia became part of [l=Sony] in the 1980s, Butler was promoted to senior vice president and executive producer (after 1988). He signed and launched the careers of a number of now famous artists including [a=Wynton Marsalis], [a=Harry Connick, Jr.] and [a=Nnenna Freelon]. His most notable achievement as a record-label executive, however, was urging jazz trumpeter [a=Miles Davis] to come out of retirement and record again.",
